      <h1>What is a Dependent Care FSA? Pre-Tax Childcare Savings</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 20, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>5 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">Childcare is one of the largest expenses for working parents. A Dependent Care FSA allows you to pay for daycare, preschool, and summer camps with pre-tax dollars, saving you thousands.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Tax benefit:</strong> Contributions to a Dependent Care FSA are deducted from your paycheck before federal, state, and FICA taxes are calculated. For a family in the 22% tax bracket, contributing the maximum amount can save over $1,500 annually.</div>

      <h2>What is a Dependent Care FSA?</h2>
      <p>A Dependent Care Flexible Spending Account (DCFSA) is a pre-tax benefit account sponsored by employers. It allows you to set aside portion of your salary to pay for qualified care services for dependents who live with you while you and your spouse work or search for work.</p>

      <h2>Who qualifies as a dependent?</h2>
      <p>To use DCFSA funds, the care must be provided for a qualifying individual:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A child under the age of 13 whom you claim as a dependent on your taxes.</li>
        <li>A spouse who is physically or mentally incapable of self-care.</li>
        <li>An adult dependent (such as an elderly parent) who lives with you and is incapable of self-care.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Annual contribution limits</h2>
      <p>The IRS limits how much you can contribute to a Dependent Care FSA. For married couples filing jointly and single parents, the limit is typically $5,000 per family per year. For married couples filing separately, the limit is $2,500 per spouse.</p>

      <h2>What expenses are eligible?</h2>
      <p>You can use Dependent Care FSA funds to pay for services that allow you to work. Eligible expenses include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Nursery schools, preschools, and daycare centers.</li>
        <li>Before-school and after-school care programs.</li>
        <li>Summer day camps (overnight camps do not qualify).</li>
        <li>Babysitters or nannies (provided they are not your dependents and you report their earnings).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Expenses that are not eligible include school tuition (kindergarten and above), tutoring, enrichment classes, and overnight camps.</p>

      <h2>Use-it-or-lose-it rule</h2>
      <p>Like medical FSAs, Dependent Care FSAs are governed by the use-it-or-lose-it rule. You must estimate your childcare costs accurately and spend all allocated funds before the plan year ends. Any leftover funds are forfeited.</p>
